			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">albailey wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp;LDA #$00<br />&nbsp;STA $2006<br />&nbsp;STA $2006<br /></div></div>
<br />Just for the record, the "standard" way to set up scrolling before a frame is rendered is through one write to $2000 (to set the name table bits) and two writes to $2005.
<br />
<br />Using $2006 to set the scrolling is a bit "hacky", and should be avoided unless necessary. Two $2006 writes alone are not enough to fully set the scrolling to any point in the name tables.
<br />
<br />I'm saying this because many people "fix" demos by writing zeroes to $2006, while they should be using $2000 (writing %xxxxxx00) and $2005 (writing $00 twice) instead. Maybe it's because writing to $2006 is easier.
<br />
<br />The cases where the use of $2006 is necessary are when you need to set the scroll after VBlank has ended (ie, when you enable rendering late or when you have a split screen). But even then, you need $2006 only if you have to set the vertical scroll.</div>

